esting and care teams\ninto those homes today? ","index":"00229","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon.\nBrian </b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097348\">Pallister</a></b><b>�(Premier):</b>\nThat's a legitimate question, Madam Speaker. ","index":"00230","speaker":"Brian Pallister"},{"html":"����� The\nincreases in testing have been fourfold over the last number of weeks in our\nprovince, and that's significant. It's a challenge all over the world. ","index":"00231","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nmember raises an important issue. The need for help in our vulnerable\npopulations, among those who, in particular, care for our vulnerable\npopulation, is very real. And it is one that we are addressing. ","index":"00232","speaker":""},{"html":"����� And I\nwould appreciate any suggestions the member may have in respect of how we might\nadd to&nbsp;&nbsp;the numbers of people that we have already added in areas\nlike personal-care homes, hospitals, in the schools, with respect to our\ntesting facilities and response to our testing. Because these are�this is a government\nthat's open to ideas and suggestions. We're acting on many. We'll continue to,\nand we'll face this challenge together. ","index":"00233","speaker":""},{"html":"����� I'd\ninvite him to be on team Manitoba.","index":"00234","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Madam\nSpeaker:</b> The honourable member for St.&nbsp;Boniface, on a supplementary\nquestion. ","index":"00235","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDougald </b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097350\">Lamont</a></b><b>�(St.\nBoniface):</b> I do have a suggestion, actually. ","index":"00236","speaker":"Dougald Lamont"},{"html":"����� Since\nlast week, we've been swamped with calls from small businesses who aren't\neligible for the new Bridge Grant program: brick and mortar businesses who\nclosed by 75 per cent but not entirely, people with multiple locations and\nespecially home-based businesses�event planners, photographers, could be\ndeejays, painting, construction. They risk being wiped out because the new\nplans don't cover them. ","index":"00237","speaker":""},{"html":"����� As one\nwriter put it, quote, our income is fair game for provincial taxation, but our\nbusinesses are treated as passive hobbies. ","index":"00238","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Will\nthe Premier change the Bridge Grant program to ensure that businesses that have\nbeen left out can survive? ","index":"00239","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon. Brian\n</b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097351\">Pallister</a></b><b>�(Premier):</b>\nWell, I think that's a refreshing change for the member to raise an issue of\nimportance like the support for small businesses, which is the most generous in\nCanada, bar none. ","index":"00240","speaker":"Brian Pallister"},{"html":"����� Ontario\njust announced a doubling of their support for small businesses last week, from\n$300&nbsp;&nbsp;million to $600 million. Ontario is 10 times our&nbsp;&nbsp;size.\nThat would be equivalent to us offering $60&nbsp;&nbsp;million of supports to\nour small businesses. Madam Speaker, we're offering four times that much in\nsupport. ","index":"00241","speaker":""},{"html":"����� And in\nrespect of the member's request that we take a look at broadening the bridge\nsupport to the businesses he raised, that is already being researched, and we\nare very open to the idea. ","index":"00242","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon. Jon </b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097353\">Gerrard</a></b><b>�(River\nHeights):</b> Madam Speaker, the provincial government has the opportunity to\nsave lives from the cold by acting now to open government buildings with\nwashrooms and places for people to sit day and night. ","index":"00243","speaker":"Jon Gerrard"},{"html":"����� The\ngrowing homeless population needs reliable and accessible places to wash their\nhands as they face increasing barriers with the closure of libraries and\ncommunity centres in addition to coffee shop restrictions due to COVID-19. ","index":"00244","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nProvince and the City together own many buildings that could open their doors\nto help people struggling in the cold as emergency shelter spaces are also\nreduced. ","index":"00245","speaker":""},{"html":"����� I ask:\nWill the Premier act before it is too late to make enough warm places\naccessible for our friends on the street who are homeless? ","index":"00246","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon.\nBrian </b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097354\">Pallister</a></b><b>�(Premier):</b>\nThis is a new trend, I hope, Madam Speaker, and I encourage the Liberal members\nof our Chamber to continue along this vein, as opposed to recording\nconversations surreptitiously. I appreciate the member raising the concern. ","index":"00247","speaker":"Brian Pallister"},{"html":"����� I will\nsay this that most importantly, our numbers, in terms of contacts, have to come\ndown. And I wanted to say thank you, while I had the opportunity, to all of the\nfolks who listened to the admonitions from Dr. Roussin, myself and many others\nto not bombard our shopping centres and facilities just prior to the\nrestrictions�the new restrictions coming in. ","index":"00248","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Those\nrestrictions are hard. They're hard on small businesses. We know that, but our\nsmall-business population responded admirably, framing off sections of their\nstores, making sure that they accommodated people. And the customers responded\nby not badger�ing people in frustration with these changes. ","index":"00249","speaker":""},{"html":"����� And so\nI thank the members for their questions and we'll certainly be willing to work\nwith them if they continue with this positive tone�welcome them to team\nManitoba, if they choose to stay. ","index":"00250","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Ms.\nJanice </b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097356\">Morley-Lecomte</a></b><b>�(Seine\nRiver):</b> Madam Speaker, as we fight back against the COVID-19 pandemic, our\ngovernment is committed to protecting vulnerable Manitobans and the people who\nserve them every day. ","index":"00251","speaker":"Janice Morley-Lecomte"},{"html":"����� Can\nthe Minister of Families update the House on how we are supporting staff to\nensure they are providing quality care to vulnerable Manitobans in our\ndisability, child-care and Child and Family Services sectors? ","index":"00252","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon.\nHeather </b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097357\">Stefanson</a></b><b>�(Minister\nof Families):</b> I want to thank the member for that question. ","index":"00253","speaker":"Heather Stefanson"},{"html":"����� Madam\nSpeaker, there is nothing more important to our government than protecting\nvulnerable Manitobans. That's why, last week, I was proud to announce $10\nmillion for the new pandemic staffing benefit for agencies in our disabilities,\nchild-care and Child and Family Services sectors. This benefit can be used for\novertime, staff replacement and sick leave for the hard-working staff that\nserve vulnerable Manitobans every day. ","index":"00254","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>*</b>\n(14:30)","index":"00255","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Madam\nSpeaker, I want to extend a very special thank-you to all the incredible\nfront-line workers who continue to serve vulnerable Manitobans each and every\nday during this pandemic.","index":"00256","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Thank\nyou. ","index":"00257","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDiljeet </b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097359\">Brar</a></b><b>�(Burrows):</b>\nMadam Speaker, the Association of Manitoba Municipalities<b> </b>policy\nconvention includes a resolution on changes to Crown lands. ","index":"00258","speaker":"Diljeet Brar"},{"html":"����� Delegates\nare asking for changes such as the return of unit and family transfers and the\nimplementation of a rental rate formula that doesn't place undue financial\nburden on renters and farmers. Manitobans are telling this government that the\nCrown lands leasing regulatory changes do not work for them.","index":"00259","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Will\nthis minister listen to Manitobans and reverse the changes to the Crown land\nleasing system? ","index":"00260","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon.\nBlaine </b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097360\">Pedersen</a></b><b>�(Minister\nof Agriculture and Resource Development):</b> I thank the member for the\nquestion because it allows me to expand on the legacy leases that we're doing\nso that intergenerational transfers will be able to happen with renters. ","index":"00261","speaker":"Blaine Pedersen"},{"html":"����� I\ndon't know why the member keeps advocating for unit transfers, which goes\nagainst Manitoba producers being able to pick up leases. And I should mention\nthat�while I have the chance�the member for Fort Garry (Mr.&nbsp;Wasyliw) is\nnow opposed to the Roquette pea-processing plant�the world's largest pea-processing\nplant that'll help diversify Manitoba's economy. Why are they against industry?","index":"00262","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Madam\nSpeaker:</b> The honourable member for Burrows, on supplementary question. ","index":"00263","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Brar:</b>\nI have been hearing from many concerned farmers and renters who are struggling\nto keep up with their lease payments, some of which have been increased by over\n300 per cent; beef producers who are already stressed thin with declining\nprices and market concerns due to the pandemic and there was simply no way for\nmost producers to prepare for such a dramatic rental increase.","index":"00264","speaker":"Diljeet Brar"},{"html":"����� Madam\nSpeaker, Manitoban farmers and renters are struggling under these regulatory\nchanges and they need this government's support, not for them to continue\ngouging producers.","index":"00265","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Will\nthe minister commit today to addressing this rapid increase in costs for\nproducers?","index":"00266","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon.\nBrian </b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097361\">Pallister</a></b><b>�(Premier):</b>\nI think it's important to acknowledge the passing of a pioneer in the\nconservation movement in our province, given the question's content. ","index":"00267","speaker":"Brian Pallister"},{"html":"����� Ted\nPoyser, who passed on the weekend of COVID. He was ill prior, Madam Speaker,\nbut a wonderful contributor to our conservation legacy. A member of\nthe�honoured member of the Manitoba agriculture hall of fame; very, very active\nthroughout his career in conservation in the government of Manitoba's employ\nand even more active in 40 years of retirement, advocating for programs such as\nthe ALUS program�alternative land use strategy�to encourage farmers to get on\nboard with conservation programing in a real way. ","index":"00268","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Our\ncondolences to Ted's family and many, many,&nbsp;&nbsp;many friends, Madam\nSpeaker. And a life wonderfully lived. We will miss him. ","index":"00269","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Madam\nSpeaker:</b> The time for oral questions has expired. ","index":"00270","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Madam\nSpeaker:</b><a name=\"_Toc477168022\"></a><a name=\"_Toc57097363\"></a> I have a\nruling for the House.","index":"00271","speaker":""},{"html":"����� On\nMarch 16th, 2020, the honourable member for Concordia (Mr. Wiebe) raised a\nmatter of privilege regarding the government's failure to provide certain\ninformation during a line of questioning by the honourable member for The\nMaples (Mr. Sandhu) during oral questions on March 10th, 2020, on the subject\nof the ride-share and taxi industries in Manitoba. ","index":"00272","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nmember for Concordia stated his belief that the government has not been\nforthcoming with the necessary information to enable the member for The Maples\nto report the government's decisions to his constituents. The member for\nConcordia concluded his remarks by moving, and I quote, that this issue be\nimmediately referred to a committee of this House. End quote.","index":"00273","speaker":""},{"html":"The honourable member for River Heights (Mr.&nbsp;&nbsp;Gerrard) and the\nhonourable member for Rossmere (Mr. Micklefield) both spoke to the matter of\nprivilege before the Deputy Speaker took it under advisement, and I thank all\nhonourable members for their advice to the Chair on this matter. ","index":"00274","speaker":""},{"html":"In order to be ruled in order as a prima facie case of privilege,\nmembers must demonstrate that the issue has been raised at the earliest\nopportunity, and also provide sufficient evidence that the privileges of the\nHouse or the privileges of individual members have been breached.","index":"00275","speaker":""},{"html":"Regarding timeliness, the honourable member for Concordia stated that he\nrequired time to review Hansard before raising his matter of privilege.\nHowever, the oral questions period to which he referred occurred on March 10th,\nand the member raised the matter before the House on March 16th. This is\ncertainly sufficient time to review Hansard, and I am therefore ruling that the\ncondition of timeliness was not met in this case.","index":"00276","speaker":""},{"html":"Regarding the second condition of whether a prima facie case has been\ndemonstrated, the honourable member for Concordia argued that his matter has\nimpeded his ability to give a clear picture to his constituents and give them\nthe opportunity to raise their concerns.","index":"00277","speaker":""},{"html":"For the information of all members, parlia�mentary privilege is a\nconstitutional right passed on to the Parliament of Canada and to the\nprovincial legislatures from the United Kingdom's 1689 Bill of Rights, and was\nincorporated into the Canadian experience to provide protection for members to\nexercise their parliamentary duties free from interference.","index":"00278","speaker":""},{"html":"I would remind the House that the individual protections for members under\nparliamentary privilege include the freedom of speech; the freedom from arrest\nand civil actions; exemptions from jury duty; freedom from obstruction,\ninterference, intimidation and molestation; and the exemption from attendance\nas a witness. ","index":"00279","speaker":""},{"html":"In order for a prima facie case of privilege to be found, one or more of\nthese individual protections would need to be demonstrated to have been\nviolated.","index":"00280","speaker":""},{"html":"Based on his comments in the House on March&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;16, 2020,\nthe honourable member for Concordia appears to have a grievance against the\ngovernment regarding the content of the government's answers during oral\nquestions.","index":"00281","speaker":""},{"html":"As Speaker Hickes ruled in 2009, the Speaker is not responsible for the\nquality or contents of replies to questions. As well, a member may put a question\nbut has no right to insist upon an answer. ","index":"00282","speaker":""},{"html":"Speaker Reid also explained in a 2013 ruling, and I quote, the Speaker\ncannot determine whether or not the answer is appropriate to the question that\nwas asked, end quote.","index":"00283","speaker":""},{"html":"Further, a 1980 ruling by Speaker Sauv� of the House of Commons states\nthat, and I quote: While I am only too aware of the multiple responsibilities,\nduties and also the work the member has to do relating to his constituency, as\nSpeaker I am required to consider only those matters which affect the member's\nparliamentary work. That is to say, whatever duty a member has to his\nconstituents, before a valid question of privilege arises in respect of any\nalleged interference, such interference must relate to the member's\nparliamentary duties. In other words, just as a member is protected from\nanything he does while taking part in a proceeding in Parliament, so too must\ninterference relate to the member's role in the context of parliamentary work.","index":"00284","speaker":""},{"html":"<b><span lang=\"EN-US\">����� </span></b><span lang=\"EN-US\">Accordingly, I am\nruling that this matter does not constitute a prima facie case of breach of\nprivilege.</span>","index":"00285","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>MLA Uzoma\n</b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097366\">Asagwara</a></b><b>�(Union Station):</b> Madam Speaker, I wish to present the following\npetition to the Legislative Assembly. ","index":"00286","speaker":"Uzoma Asagwara"},{"html":"����� To the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba, the background to this\npetition is as follows: ","index":"00287","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (1) The provincial government plans to close the Dauphin\nCorrectional Centre, DCC, in May 2020.","index":"00288","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (2) The DCC is one of the largest employers in Dauphin, providing\nthe community with good, family-supporting jobs.","index":"00289","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (3) Approximately 80 families will be directly affected by the\nclosure, which will also impact the local economy. ","index":"00290","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (4) As of January 27, 2020, Manitoba's justice system was already\nmore than 250 inmates overcapacity.","index":"00291","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We petition the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as follows:","index":"00292","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To urge the Minister of Justice to immediately reverse the decision\nto close the DCC and proceed with the previous plan to build a new correctional\nand healing centre with an expanded courthouse in Dauphin.","index":"00293","speaker":""},{"html":"����� This\nhas been signed by many Manitobans. ","index":"00294","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Nello\n</b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097368\">Altomare</a></b><b>�(Transcona):</b> It's my pleasure to bring the following petition to\nthe Manitoba Legislative Assembly.","index":"00295","speaker":"Nello Altomare"},{"html":"����� The background\nto this petition is as follows:","index":"00296","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>*</b>\n(14:40)","index":"00297","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (1) On September 4, 2020, the provincial government announced that\nCancerCare outpatient services will be cut at the Concordia Hospital and Seven\nOaks General Hospital, effective December 2020.� ","index":"00298","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (2)� Closing\ntwo CancerCare sites in Winnipeg will mean a third of existing sites are lost,\nwith increased burdens placed on outpatient cancer services at the Health\nSciences Centre and St. Boniface Hospital. ","index":"00299","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (3)� The\ncut of these outpatient services has provoked concerns from health-care workers\nand CancerCare nurses alike, who have stressed to the provincial government\nthat the cut is contrary to what CancerCare Manitoba's goals of patient care\nare and would most certainly increase the burden for the people they are trying\nto help. ","index":"00300","speaker":""},{"html":"����� CancerCare\nnurses have also noted that this decision has more to do with saving money\nrather than it was in the best interests of patients. This is further\nhighlighted by a 2019 consulting contract bid, which shows that this cut has\nbeen made purely in the interest of fiscal performance and will not improve the\nquality of patient care. ","index":"00301","speaker":""},{"html":"(5)� Patients who do not have access to a vehicle or reliable\ntransportation will be hit the hardest by this cut with the burden of falling\nlargely on seniors and Manitobans on low incomes. ","index":"00302","speaker":""},{"html":"(6)� Cuts within the Winnipeg Regional Health Authority, including the\nprovincial government's closure of the Concordia emergency room and Seven Oaks\nemergency room, have already compromised health-care access close to home for\nresidents of northeast and northwest Winnipeg. ","index":"00303","speaker":""},{"html":"(7)� Deterioration of the health care within Winnipeg Regional Health\nAuthority has led to increased wait times, compromised patient care and\nworsened health outcomes. This cut will only continue to deteriorate the\nquality of care for patients while forcing more demands onto health-care\nworkers. ","index":"00304","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We\npetition the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as follows: ","index":"00305","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To\nurge the provincial government to halt its proposed closure of CancerCare sites\nat the Concordia Hospital and Seven Oaks General Hospital, while guaranteeing\naccess to high-quality outpatient CancerCare services in northeast and\nnorthwest Winnipeg. ","index":"00306","speaker":""},{"html":"����� This\npetition is signed by Tony Korosevich <i>[phonetic]</i>, Becky Dilfer <i>[phonetic]</i>,\nKerry <i>[phonetic]</i> Smith and many Manitobans. ","index":"00307","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Thank\nyou, Madam Speaker. ","index":"00308","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Madam\nSpeaker:</b> In accordance with our rule 133(6), when petitions are read they\nare deemed to be received by the House. ","index":"00309","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr.\nDiljeet </b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097370\">Brar</a></b><b>�(Burrows):</b> I wish to present the following petition to the\nLegislative Assembly. ","index":"00310","speaker":"Diljeet Brar"},{"html":"����� To the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba, the background to this\npetition is as follows: ","index":"00311","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The provincial government plans to close the Dauphin Correctional\nCentre, DCC, in May 2020.","index":"00312","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The DCC is one of the largest employers in Dauphin, providing the\ncommunity with good, family-supporting jobs.","index":"00313","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Approximately 80 families will be directly affected by the closure,\nwhich will also impact the local economy. ","index":"00314","speaker":""},{"html":"����� As of January 27, 2020, Manitoba's justice system was already more\nthan 250 inmates overcapacity.","index":"00315","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We petition to Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as follows:","index":"00316","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To urge the Minister of Justice to immediately reverse the decision\nto close the DCC and proceed with the previous plan to build a new correctional\nand healing centre with an expanded courthouse in Dauphin.","index":"00317","speaker":""},{"html":"����� This\nhas been signed by many Manitobans. ","index":"00318","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Ian </b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097371\">Bushie</a></b><b>�(Keewatinook):</b> I wish to present the following petition to the\nLegislative Assembly. ","index":"00319","speaker":"Ian Bushie"},{"html":"����� To the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba, the background to this\npetition is as follows: ","index":"00320","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The provincial government plans to close the Dauphin Correctional\nCentre, DCC, in May 2020.","index":"00321","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The DCC is one of the largest employers in Dauphin, providing the\ncommunity with good, family-supporting jobs.","index":"00322","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Approximately 80 families will be directly affected by the closure,\nwhich will also impact the local economy. ","index":"00323","speaker":""},{"html":"����� As of January 27, 2020, Manitoba's justice system was already more\nthan 250 inmates overcapacity.","index":"00324","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We petition the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as follows:","index":"00325","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To urge the Minister of Justice to immediately reverse the decision\nto close the DCC and proceed with the previous plan to build a new correctional\nand healing centre with an expanded courthouse in Dauphin.","index":"00326","speaker":""},{"html":"����� This\nhas been signed by many Manitobans.� ","index":"00327","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Hon. Jon </b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097373\">Gerrard</a></b><b>�(River\nHeights):</b> Madam Speaker, I wish to present the following petition to the\nLegislative Assembly. ","index":"00328","speaker":"Jon Gerrard"},{"html":"����� The\nbackground to this petition is as follows: ","index":"00329","speaker":""},{"html":"����� There\nhas been a dramatic increase in COVID‑19 infections in Manitoba during\nthe second wave of the pandemic, to the extent that Manitoba quickly rose from\none of the lowest to having the highest number of active cases per capita of\nall provinces.","index":"00330","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nresurgence in cases is worse because the provincial government was not prepared\nfor the pandemic, resulting in very long wait times for COVID‑19 tests\nand people waiting for up to seven days to get results. ","index":"00331","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nseven-day delay for test results led to a further delay in contact tracing\nwhich, in turn, led to greater uncontrolled and undetected community spread of\nCOVID‑19.","index":"00332","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Cases\nare spreading in personal-care homes because the provincial government did not\nadequately prepare to prevent and address personal-care homes' COVID‑19\ninfections. ","index":"00333","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nprovincial government did not institute full testing of all staff and residents\nin a personal-care home when the first COVID‑19 case was detected in a\nhome. ","index":"00334","speaker":""},{"html":"����� When,\nin May and June, Manitoba Liberals' repeated calls for a rapid response team\nfor seniors homes to prepare for a second wave, the provincial government\nignored the idea and brushed it aside. ","index":"00335","speaker":""},{"html":"����� In\nAugust, the provincial government ignored the calls for investment in infection\ncontrol and better staffing to prepare seniors homes for a second wave, putting\nthe health and safety of residents and staff alike at risk.","index":"00336","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nprovincial government failed to act to address reports of poor care at the\nParkview Place personal-care home, including a March&nbsp;2020 report detailing\nconcerns with the state of repair of the facility. Its cleanliness and\nsanitation practices included issues with cockroaches, dirty toilets and\ngrease-laden dirt in the kitchen. ","index":"00337","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nMinister of Health and Seniors and Active Living has been undermining public\nhealth fundamentals by downplaying the need for masks, which are known to\nprevent the spread of contagion.","index":"00338","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nprovincial government's wishful thinking and failure to get ready for the\nsecond wave of the pandemic has imposed tremendous costs and hardship across\nManitoba, including schools and businesses. The provincial government's failure\nto take basic steps&nbsp;&nbsp;to control outbreaks has led to further\nshutdowns, and businesses have had to close or reduce&nbsp;their capacity\nwithout receiving the financial government assistance. ","index":"00339","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nprovincial government's own accounts show that support for business is among\nthe worst in Canada. Businesses continue to face bankruptcy and operating risks\nbecause the provincial government refused to step up with financial support or\nPPE so that they could continue to safely operate. Businesses and workers alike\nhave been forced to choose between getting sick or going broke.","index":"00340","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nprovincial government has been saying one thing and doing another: calling for\nfundamentals while urging people to go back to work, shop and encouraging\nbehaviour that increases the spread of COVID‑19.","index":"00341","speaker":""},{"html":"����� When\nthe Minister of Health, Seniors and Active Living was asked about preventing\ndeaths at personal‑care homes, he responded these deaths were unavoidable.\nDr.&nbsp;Nathan Stall, who specializes in geriatrics and internal medicine at a\nToronto hospital, called the notion that deaths are unavoidable ageist and\nurged the minister to reconsider. Outbreaks like the one in Winnipeg's Parkview\nPlace are avoidable tragedies, as we have seen in other jurisdictions like\nSingapore.","index":"00342","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We\npetition the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as follows:","index":"00343","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To\nurge the provincial government to call a public inquiry into the mishandling of\nthe second wave of the pandemic and into the outbreak at Parkview Place\npersonal-care home.","index":"00344","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To\nurge the provincial government to replace the current Minister of Health,\nSeniors and Active Living as a result of his failure to support personal-care\nhomes and his failure to adequately prepare the province for the second wave of\nthe pandemic. ","index":"00345","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Signed\nby Jared Adams, Jackie Spear, Brian <i>[phonetic]</i> Yeo and many other\nManitobans. ","index":"00346","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Ms. Cindy\n</b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097375\">Lamoureux</a></b><b>�(Tyndall\nPark): </b>I wish to present the following petition to the Legislative\nAssembly. ","index":"00347","speaker":"Cindy Lamoureux"},{"html":"����� The background to this petition is as follows: ","index":"00348","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The\nVivian sands project is a proposed silica sand mine and processing plant to be\nbuilt in the RM of Springfield. The overall project includes mining claims of\nover 85,000 hectares, making it the largest claim ever given to a single\ncompany in Manitoba's history. It is larger than the city of Winnipeg, which is\n46,410 hectares. ","index":"00349","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>*</b>\n(14:50)","index":"00350","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The amount of dry, solid sand mined produced per year according to\nthe EAP is 1.36&nbsp;million tons, and much of this sand will be used in\nfracking. ","index":"00351","speaker":""},{"html":"����� A major concern of the proposed mine and plant&nbsp;&nbsp;is that,\nif developed, it could contaminate the&nbsp;Sandilands aquifer, including both\ncarbonate and sandstone aquifers, which covers much of southeastern Manitoba.\nIt has excellent water quality and is the water source for tens of thousands of\nManitobans, including many municipal water systems, agriculture, industry,\nprivate wells and an abundance of wildlife and ecosystems. Further, people in\nthe Indigenous communities that are potentially affected by this were not\nafforded the required Indigenous consultation from either federal or provincial\ngovernment officials. ","index":"00352","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The sustainable yield of the combined sandstone and carbonate\naquifers has still not yet been established by the provincial authorities.","index":"00353","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The mine could cause leaching of acid, heavy metals and pollute the\naquifer, as it will go down 200&nbsp;feet into the Winnipeg formation of the\nsandstone aquifer. There is concern that the shale, which separates the\ncarbonate and sandstone aquifers will, when exposed to injected air from the\nCanWhite Sands extraction process, turn to acid. ","index":"00354","speaker":""},{"html":"����� An\nadditional concern with the proposed mine and plant is the potential to pollute\nthe Brokenhead River and the aquatic food chain leading to Lake Winnipeg. ","index":"00355","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Residents in the area have also expressed fears of being\noverexposed to silica dust during production, as there has been a demonstrated\nlack of safety and environmental procedures by the CanWhite Sands Corporation\nduring the exploratory drilling phase. Signage and fencing has been poor;\nidentifying the required mine claim tags were missing; there were no warnings\nfor silica dust exposure and no coverings to prevent exposure of the silica\nstockpiles to the elements.","index":"00356","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Residents' concerns include the fact that bore�holes, which should\nhave been promptly and properly sealed, were left open for a year. The drilling\nof hundreds of improperly sealed boreholes yearly create significant risks of\nsurface contamination, mixing of aquifer waters and drainage of surface fecal\nmatter into the aquifer.","index":"00357","speaker":""},{"html":"����� There is also a risk of subsidence around each borehole as a result\nof sand extraction.","index":"00358","speaker":""},{"html":"����� There are also potential transboundary issues that need to be\naddressed as the aquifers extend into Minnesota. ","index":"00359","speaker":""},{"html":"����� This project should not proceed, as no licensing conditions and\nmitigation measures will alleviate the&nbsp;&nbsp;risk of all Manitobans and\nthe environment since&nbsp;&nbsp;CanWhite Sands Corporation plans to use an\nunprecedented mining technique with no established safe outcome. The\ncorporation has gone on record indicating that it does not know how to mine for\nthe silica in the water supply and need to develop a new extraction methodology\nthat has never been done before.","index":"00360","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Contamination of the aquifers and the environ�ment is irreversible\nand there are many surface sources of high purity silica that can be extracted\nwithout endangering two essential regional aquifers. ","index":"00361","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We petition the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as follows:","index":"00362","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To urge the provincial government to undertake a&nbsp;&nbsp;combined\nreview of the Vivian Sand Facility processing plant and the mining/extraction\nportion of&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;the operation as a class 3 development with a&nbsp;&nbsp;review\nby Manitoba's Clean Environment Commission to include public hearings and\npartici�pant funding;","index":"00363","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To urge the provincial government to halt all activity at the mine\nand plant until the Clean Environment Commission's review is completed and the\nproject proposal has been thoroughly evaluated.","index":"00364","speaker":""},{"html":"����� This\npetition has been signed by many Manitobans. ","index":"00365","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Tom </b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097377\">Lindsey</a></b><b>�(Flin Flon): </b>I wish to present the following petition to the\nLegislative Assembly of Manitoba. ","index":"00366","speaker":"Tom Lindsey"},{"html":"����� The background to this petition is as follows: ","index":"00367","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The provincial government plans to close the Dauphin Correctional\nCentre, DCC, in May 2020.","index":"00368","speaker":""},{"html":"����� The DCC is one of the largest employers in Dauphin, providing the\ncommunity with good, family-supporting jobs.","index":"00369","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Approximately 80 families will be directly affected by the closure,\nwhich will also impact the local economy.� ","index":"00370","speaker":""},{"html":"����� As of January 27th, 2020, Manitoba's justice system was already\nmore than 250 inmates over�capacity.","index":"00371","speaker":""},{"html":"����� We petition the Legislative Assembly of Manitoba as follows:","index":"00372","speaker":""},{"html":"����� To urge the Minister of Justice to immediately reverse the decision\nto close the DCC and proceed with the previous plan to build a new correctional\nand healing centre with an expanded courthouse in Dauphin.","index":"00373","speaker":""},{"html":"����� And\nthis petition, Madam Speaker, has been signed by Muriel Thwaitke <i>[phonetic],</i>\nJade Toner <i>[phonetic]</i> and Matthew Sliworsky <i>[phonetic]</i><b> </b>and\nmany other Manitobans.","index":"00374","speaker":""},{"html":"����� Thank\nyou.","index":"00375","speaker":""},{"html":"<b>Mr. Jim </b><b><a name=\"_Toc57097378\">Maloway</a></b><b>�(Elmwood):</b> I wish to present the following petition to the\nLegislative Assembly. ","index":"00376","speaker":"Jim Maloway"},{"html":"����� The background to this petition is as follows: ","index":"00377","speaker":""},{"html":"����� (1) The